            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Not Cleaning Dishes Properly</h3>
              <p>
                When a dishwasher doesn’t clean dishes effectively, it could be
                due to a clogged spray arm, a malfunctioning pump assembly, or
                low water temperature. Mineral deposits or food particles
                blocking the spray arm can prevent water from reaching all
                dishes. A faulty pump assembly may lead to insufficient water
                pressure, and a defective heating element or thermostat might
                mean the water isn't hot enough for thorough cleaning. Regular
                maintenance, such as cleaning filters and spray arms, can
                improve performance.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Not Draining</h3>
              <p>
                If the dishwasher is not draining, it might be due to a clogged
                drain hose, a faulty drain pump, or a blocked filter. A kinked
                or obstructed drain hose can prevent water from exiting the
                dishwasher. Similarly, if the drain pump is malfunctioning, it
                won't be able to expel water properly. Cleaning the filter and
                ensuring the drain hose is clear can resolve many drainage
                issues. In some cases, replacing the drain pump might be
                necessary.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Leaking</h3>
              <p>
                Leaks can be caused by a damaged door seal, a faulty water inlet
                valve, or a cracked hose. A worn or misaligned door seal can
                allow water to escape from the door during operation. If the
                water inlet valve is defective, it might leak water even when
                the dishwasher is off. Cracks in hoses or loose connections can
                also lead to leaks. Inspecting and replacing damaged components
                can prevent leaks and protect surrounding areas from water
                damage.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Not Filling with Water</h3>
              <p>
                When a dishwasher doesn’t fill with water, the problem might lie
                with the water inlet valve, the float switch, or the electronic
                control board. A defective water inlet valve might not open to
                allow water into the dishwasher. A stuck float switch can
                mistakenly signal that the dishwasher is full, preventing it
                from filling. Issues with the control board can also disrupt the
                water-filling cycle. Testing these components and replacing
                faulty ones can restore proper water intake.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Making Strange Noises</h3>
              <p>
                Unusual noises often indicate issues with the pump assembly,
                motor, or spray arm. A worn pump assembly might produce grinding
                or buzzing sounds, while a malfunctioning motor can cause
                humming or squealing noises. Loose or blocked spray arms can
                also create rattling sounds. Identifying the source of the noise
                and replacing or repairing the affected parts can help silence
                the dishwasher and ensure smooth operation.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Not Starting</h3>
              <p>
                If the dishwasher doesn’t start, it could be due to a faulty
                door latch, a broken touchpad, or an issue with the electronic
                control board. A door latch that isn’t securing properly can
                prevent the dishwasher from beginning its cycle. A
                non-responsive touchpad may hinder input selection, and a
                malfunctioning control board can disrupt the entire operation.
                Inspecting these components andreplacing defective ones can
                resolve start-up issues.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Not Drying Dishes</h3>
              <p>
                Inadequate drying can result from a malfunctioning heating
                element, a faulty thermostat, or improper loading. If the
                heating element isn’t working, the dishwasher won’t generate the
                necessary heat for drying. A defective thermostat might not
                regulate the temperature correctly, leading to poor drying
                performance. Ensuring dishes are loaded properly to allow air
                circulation can also improve drying results. Testing and
                replacing faulty parts can restore effective drying.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Door Won’t Close</h3>
              <p>
                A dishwasher door that won’t close could be due to a broken door
                latch, misaligned racks, or a damaged door seal. A faulty door
                latch might prevent the door from securing tightly. Misaligned
                racks can obstruct the door from closing properly, and a damaged
                door seal might create resistance. Inspecting and adjusting
                these components can help ensure the door closes securely,
                allowing the dishwasher to operate correctly.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Smells Bad</h3>
              <p>
                Foul odors often result from food particles trapped in the
                filter, spray arms, or drain hose. A clogged filter can harbor
                bacteria and food debris, leading to unpleasant smells. Blocked
                spray arms and drain hoses can also contribute to odor issues by
                preventing proper water circulation and drainage. Regularly
                cleaning these components and running a cycle with dishwasher
                cleaner can eliminate bad smells and maintain a fresh interior.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Buttons Not Working</h3>
              <p>
                Non-responsive buttons are typically due to a faulty touchpad,
                control panel, or electrical connections. A worn-out touchpad
                might not register selections, and issues with the control panel
                can disrupt the interface. Loose or damaged electrical
                connections can also prevent buttons from working. Inspecting
                and securing connections, cleaning the touchpad, or replacing
                the control panel can resolve these issues.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dishwasher Overflows</h3>
              <p>
                Overflowing can be caused by a malfunctioning float switch, a
                faulty water inlet valve, or a clogged drain hose. If the float
                switch fails to regulate the water level correctly, it can
                result in overfilling. A broken water inlet valve might not shut
                off water flow when required. Blockages in the drain hose can
                prevent proper water drainage, leading to overflow. Testing and
                replacing faulty components can prevent overflows and ensure
                safe operation.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
